<h2>ICS 269, Spring 2006: Theory Seminar</h2>

<h3>Jun 9, 2006, in CS 243</h3>

<h1>The Santa Claus Problem</h1>

<h2>Authored by: Nikhil Bansal and Maxim Sviridenko</h2>

<h2>Presented by Matt Nguyen</h2>

<p>
Abstract:
<p>
The Santa Claus Problem is defined as follows:  Santa Claus has <I>n</I> presents 
that he wants to distribute among <I>m</I> kids.  Each kid has an arbitrary value 
for each present.  Let <I>p<sub>ij</sub></I> be the value kid <I>i</I> has for present <I>j</I>.  Santa's 
goal is to distribute presents in such a way that the least lucky kid is 
as happy as possible.  That is, max&nbsp;min<sub><I>i</I></sub>&nbsp;Sum(of among items given to kid <I>i</I>)  <I>p<sub>ij</sub></I>.

The authors give an <I>O</I>(log&nbsp;log&nbsp;<I>m</I>&nbsp;/&nbsp;log&nbsp;log&nbsp;log&nbsp;<I>m</I>) approximation for the 
restricted assignment case of the problem where <I>p<sub>ij</sub></I> is in {<I>p<sub>j</sub></I>, 0} (That 
is, each present <I>j</I> has either value <I>p<sub>j</sub></I> or 0 for each kid}.
<p>
(from STOC 2006)
